This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. How many science fiction works feature spacecraft capable of planet hopping, interstellar travel, or even galaxy galloping? Yet in our experience we know it takes several days travel to reach even the moon and years to reach the nearest planets. Travel to the stars is presently unthinkable. In space opera, the writer usually invokes some kind of faster than light drive which glosses over the basics of the special theory of relativity. We asked physicist and science fiction writer Robert Forward how it may be possible to travel faster than light. When you talk about going faster than light, really what you want to do is get from here to there without traveling all the steps in between. If you can do that, then you can go faster than light. There are two ways at least that I know to do that. One is to find a space warp. You jump into the space warp, you go into a hyperspace, and then you come out of another space warp somewhere else in our universe. And if you can do that in a time shorter than it takes you to travel over the top line, then you've done that. And the amazing thing about it is the Einstein General Theory of relativity has space warps in it. Going through a space warp is one way to get around the speed of light limit. And what's the second way? Then the other way to go faster and speed up light is to destroy the space between you and where you want to go. Now this space drive theory was invented by a student of Roger Penrose. He's a scientific expert and relativist that works with Hawking on gravitation. And he's working on a thing called twister theory. And in the twister theory, the real universe is not what we see. That's only a reduced image of it. The real universe is an eight-dimensional universe that's made up of twisters. The twisters not only make up all the particles in the space and time that we live in, it even makes up the space and the time. It takes a certain collection of twisters to make up a point in space. It takes another collection of twisters to make up a point in time. This collection of twisters is a fairly uniform thing, and that's why we see space as it is according to Penrose. Now we don't know whether the twister theory is correct, but Roger is hoping that it will turn out to be an accurate method, I mean accurate theory for the interest. So how does one build a faster than light drive based on the twister theory of Penrose and his students? If you want the twister space too much, give it a real strong warp, then it's no longer ordered well enough to make a piece of space or a piece of time. So if you take a piece of twister space and you warp it badly, the space and the time that it used to make now disappears. It's no longer there. So their version of a different kind of a faster than light drive is you take a spacecraft up, you get it out in the wave in the planets and so forth, then you turn on the twister warping machine in your spacecraft on the side parts Alpha Centauri and you just warp that space so much that you warp that twister space so much that the space time between here and Alpha Centauri disappears. And what you'll see if you're sitting in the spacecraft is that all of a sudden Alpha Centauri just come right towards you and then pretty soon you look out one window, you see the sun, you look out the other window, you'll see Alpha Centauri. Then the machine inside the spacecraft unwarps the space but on the other side of the spacecraft and all that space now reappears between the spacecraft and the sun, you watch the sun recede off another distance while you stay there with Alpha Centauri. So that's another way to get there. You just get rid of the space between here and there. This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. No other field has fans as distinctive and intense, some would even say as fanatical, Science Fiction does. Every year there are hundreds of conventions around the country, from small local affairs to the incredible world convention in which fans gather. They come for various reasons of course, to socialize with like-minded people, to meet science fiction and fantasy authors, to buy books at the dealer's tables. There's one particular type of fan with a special, consuming interest, costuming and masquerade. Most conventions therefore have a masquerade section, a contest for fans who have made and presented a costume from some science fiction or fantasy work. The Science Fiction Radio Show spoke with Teresa Patterson, a fan who has won numerous awards for her science fiction and fantasy costuming. She says a few years ago she was hooked on Star Trek but do nothing about fandom. But one day after Star Trek there was a big advertisement for a Star Trek convention in Dallas and it was going to have some of the stars there and everything and I'd never heard of such a thing. But it sounded like a lot of fun so we went down and then I ran into nearly 1500 to 2000 fans who also liked Star Trek, who also had a reason for coming to Science Fiction and Fantasy and had been touched by Star Trek because of this feeling they had and all of a sudden I had a family and a place to belong and I've been an avid fan ever since going to as many conventions as I could and one aspect of this convention was costuming and I'd always been sort of interested in theater and that sort of thing but never really involved. But here were all these people who weren't really in the theater and weren't performers but they had all these wonderful costumes and were going up and doing the masquerades. The next time they had a convention I was ready and I had my first costume it was a very poorly made mirror mirror costume from the Star Trek episode Mirror Mirror. But it was a beginning and it was something and all of a sudden I was involved and I had a part in a world where in my male life I didn't have much of anything that I really belonged to and through fandom and science fiction and belonging to that world I eventually learned how to belong in a normal world again and basically it changed my entire life. I actually even became popular in high school which at the time that I started in fandom I would have thought that popularity was something I would never see. So and then it grew from there I became a theater and drama major at UTA and I now work as a professional singer and performer and do a lot of costuming with that job and freelance costuming but my first love is still making characters come alive on the stage at science fiction and fantasy conventions because I think that what I was searching for at the time was a reality that I could fit into and I think that's what the other fans are searching for and the masquerade gives me a chance to make that dream become a reality. Radio Show, so stay with us. This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy. And here are your hosts. This is Darrel Lane and David Carson. Teresa Patterson is a science fiction fantasy fan who was turned on by the idea of making familiar characters from the field come to life for others. She goes to science fiction conventions with carefully constructed costumes and colorful skits. She enters the masquerade or some costuming competition with her creations and has won many awards. Costuming is a fascinating part of science fiction fandom. We observe that there must be some acting ability that goes along with it. Of course, but actually I think there's a bit of actress or actor in almost everyone who's into the fandom scene at all and even people who aren't. It's just a matter of whether we can actually do something with it or not. A lot of people just assume, well, that'll never happen. I'll never get to do anything with it. And they forget about that part of their personality. I'm a little more stubborn. I intend to do it professionally eventually. And to some extent, I'm doing that now with my performing as a singer and dancer with the singing telegram companies and as a model and so forth. And I've been in two science fiction movies as an extra, Logan's Run and Laid of Heaven, which both were a lot of fun. But it doesn't take an actor or an actress to do these kind of things. And I've seen a lot of really wonderful skits and costumes and performances pulled off by people who had never even considered the idea of being professional actors or actresses. They just want to make it real. And that's all acting ever was, was just trying to make something real and recreate something. It's just that what we do is a little different than your typical stage play. But it should be no less entertaining and we're trying to create it so that it's no less entertaining. Patterson usually works with a group of friends in performing her mass grade skits. Who wondered how newcomers took to costuming. Do they become converts fairly quickly? We don't have anyone who's ever met or joined our group that hasn't immediately ended up in a costume. Sometimes under protest the first time, but they always end up under a costume and then they always want more and more costumes. And the next thing you know, we've got a whole new set of costumers. When we went to Boston, we took five people in four different costume skits. These five people, I was the only one who'd ever been to a world com before. Most of them had never even been to a major convention before. All they knew was they wanted to do the masquerade. They loved science fiction and fantasy and fandom and they wanted to do the masquerade. And they had a lot of creativity and they were willing to listen to suggestions and we all worked together. And we came away with four awards. People who nobody had ever heard of before, we went up there to the world con and won four of the top awards. Best presentation overall, first runner up for best presentation. Star Wars special award prize and first runner up for best fantasy. We asked Patterson how she taught herself to do the elaborate costuming she's doing now. I still don't know what I'm doing now. It's, I've learned a lot from other people and from lots of trial and error, mostly trial and error. I discovered fabric glue when I was in desperation and it works wonderfully on all kinds of things. When I started costuming, I really didn't know anything about sewing at all. The idea of making clothes was the farthest thing from my mind. And it just happened that I needed a costume and I had to figure out how to create this thing that you couldn't possibly buy in a store by its very nature. And the first costumes were very much trial and error. But since then I've learned a lot of shortcuts, shortcuts that an average seamstress would probably never use because they learned all the rules and I didn't. And I try to pass on those shortcuts and a lot of the major conventions, they have workshops where they discuss costuming and shortcuts that other people have find and stage techniques. And there are books and magazines out that cover costuming and make up and easy ways to do all these things. Any fan who's seen some of Theresa Patterson's work can't help but be impressed. She's made many characters from fantasy and science fiction live. We'll talk about some other aspects of fandom on our next show. This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas. Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us. This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy. And here are your hosts. This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. This will be our final show with Theresa Patterson, Science Fiction Fan and Costume Designer. Patterson talks about the various types of science fiction fans. And our listeners should keep in mind that in fan terminology, fin is the plural of fan. There are actually several different level of fans. There are new fin which are people who just discovered that oh you mean there's somebody else that reads this stuff besides me. There are true fin who are the people who go to conventions on a live and die situation and fandom is a way of life and will sell whatever they can sell at the dealer's tables if they can make enough money to get back and forth between the conventions and who literally the convention society is their social life. Then there are a whole scope of people in between. There are what we call closet fans who are the people who read the books, who watch the shows, who go to the movies, but who have absolutely no idea that there's any kind of organization out there whatsoever. There are the slightly organized fans which are people who realize that there is organization who maybe go to a con every now and then, who every now and then get a chance to meet their favorite author, but who really aren't that much into the convention scene. It's just something that they like and every now and then they like to express the fact that they enjoy it. And then of course there are the professional fan which are people who through their professions one way or the other have somehow gotten tied up with the science fiction or fantasy genre and because they deal with it every day or part of every day and because they must like it or they wouldn't deal with it to some extent. They're fan too. Serious science fiction fans who attend conventions live in a weird sort of world with its own activities and even its own vocabulary. Both these aspects of fandom are illustrated in the word, folk singing. We asked Patterson to explain it to us. Well basically like any other, when you take fandom as a microcosm of people and that this is their social life when they're at a convention, you have to deal with the fact that social life includes entertainment. And if you're into science fiction and fantasy and you're doing something special like a convention, you don't want to go out and entertain yourself by going to the local bar or the local disco. That's boring. You want to do something that's uniquely fandom. And so something that was developed through fandom is a thing called folk singing. Folk singing is folk singing sort of. Basically, folk singing is a creation of songs that are performed by one person or many person on or off or on the same page. So in one song, it's a song that's written specifically for the audience of science fiction and fantasy listeners. Patterson says there can be different kinds of folk singing but that they all fulfill a need among science fiction fans. Now some of folk singing is very simple. It simply involves taking a tune from a normal song and changing the words around to have something to do with science fiction or fantasy. And usually those are funny and they're the kind that you can get a lot of giggles off and everyone joins in. But the more serious element is original songs that deal with very serious ideas like the fact that man's finally reaching for space and the Columbia's here or the fact that when are we really going to get to be dancing on the moon by the time it actually happens I'll be too old and things like that. And Filking is a whole type of folk singing strictly for fans. And some fans don't like it because they don't like the taking of other people's music and putting other lyrics to it. But for most fans it's a wonderful outlet for getting to know other people and just sit around at night when there's nothing else to do and sing songs and get a very close type of camaraderie that you only get in some other kind of very close knit group. Not all conventions have folk singing but the more intimate ones where it really is a social life type situation do because it's a very big part of the social life. Patterson's enthusiasm for science fiction and science fiction fandom is obvious and infectious. This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.
